Title: MongoDB.local SF 2018
Description:
MongoDB is coming to SF! Join us for a full-day educational conference covering the fundamentals to advanced techniques of app design and performance management. You’ll hear from the team that builds the database and power users running MongoDB deployments.
At MongoDB.local SF, we'll also host our first annual Women in Tech luncheon. Luncheon attendees will be able to participate in additional networking opportunities and will receive special swag. 
This day of learning will close with a happy hour. Register now to claim your seat.
WHAT YOU'LL LEARN
Insight into building applications with MongoDB Stitch, the serverless platform from MongoDB
How to deploy, operate, and scale your database on all major cloud platforms with MongoDB Atlas
What’s new in MongoDB 4.0, including multi-document ACID transactions, and how the latest version of MongoDB can help your business succeed
Best practices from the experts on topics including schema design, analytics, microservices, performance, and more
Register for hands-on, deep-dive technical sessions, equipping you with the tools you need to build and deploy your giant ideas

Title: Copyrighting all the melodies to avoid accidental infringement | Damien Riehl | TEDxMinneapolis
Description: In the litany of copyright infringement lawsuits, technology lawyer and musician Damien Riehl demonstrates that music is merely math, and has a finite number of possible melodies. If you’ve ever thought a song you like sounded similar to another, the culprit may not be an unethical forger, but rather the limited mathematical musical equations that our favorite artists have to work with.  Current copyright law is at risk of severely limiting future music creation and future human creativity. This talk suggests a new way to handle these legal cases.  Damien Riehl is a technology lawyer with a B.S. in music. After beginning to code in 1985, and for the web in 1995, he has worked for the chief judges of state and federal courts; litigated for a decade; taught law-school copyright classes; and led teams in software development, digital forensics, proactive cybersecurity, reactive cybersecurity incidents, and world-scale investigations. Damien’s combined experience in the law, technology, and music has inspired his most recent project—copyrighting billions of unique melodies. This talk was given at a TEDx event using the TED conference format but independently organized by a local community. Learn more at https://www.ted.com/tedx
